==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Farrow
<hw>Far"row</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Farrowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Farrowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To bring forth (young); -- said
only of swine.</def> <rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farrow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Farrow
<hw>Far"row</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Scot. <ets>ferry cow</ets> a
cow that is not with calf, D. <ets>vaarkoe</ets>, <ets>vaars</ets>,
heifer, G. <ets>f⟦aum⟧rse</ets>, AS. <ets>fearr</ets> bull, G.
<ets>farre</ets>. Cf. <er>Heifer</er>.]</ety> <def>Not producing young
in a given season or year; -- said only of cows.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ If a cow has had a calf, but fails in a subsequent year,
she is said to be <xex>farrow</xex>, or to go
<xex>farrow</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farry</ent>⟦br⟧
